Package tools.data.array

Class ArrayTools

  • java.lang.Object
    • tools.data.array.ArrayTools
  • public final class ArrayTools
extends java.lang.Object
    The Array class provides static methods to dynamically resolve primitive typed arrays mixed with object arrays.
    It re-implements the get, set and length functions for primitive types of the Array class, and the toDeepString function of the Arrays class in pure java code. Because of this, JIT can optimize the code better compared to the native implementations of the reflect array class.

    The functions permits widening conversions to occur during a get or set operation, but throws an ClassCastException if a narrowing conversion would occur.
    See Also:
    Array, Arrays

      • toDeepString

        public static java.lang.String toDeepString​(java.lang.Object array)
        Creates a deep string representation of the given multi-dimensional array.

        If the given object is not an array, then simply Object.toString(). is used for the string representation. This is also used the values inside the array.

        This function supports multi-dimensional arrays.

        Format

        The format of the returned string is as follows:
        #dimensions #elements Result
        10"[]"
        11"[v1]"
        13"[v1, v2, v3]"
        20,0"[]"
        21,0"[[]]"
        22,0"[[], []]"
        22,1"[[v1], [v2]]"
        22,2"[[v1, v2], [v3, v4]]"
        Here, v1, v2, ... , vn are the string values are of the objects inside the array.
        Note that the separators of both the elements and the arrays are ", ", or a colon followed by a space.
        If an element or array is null, then the entire contents of that element or array is replaced by "null".
        Parameters:
        array - The array to print.
        Returns:
        A string representation of the given array.

      • toDeepString

        public static java.lang.String toDeepString​(java.lang.Object array,
                                            int radix)
                                     throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Converts the given integer typed number array to a string representation in base radix.
        This means that the types byte, short, char, int, long, their class equivalents, and custom types extending Number are allowed.
        Floating point numbers (float and double are INVALID, as well as classes not extending Number.
        Parameters:
        array - The integer typed array to print.
        radix - The radix of the values.
        Returns:
        The String representation as specified by Arrays.toString(Object[]).
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If the given object has the wrong type.
        See Also:
        Integer.toString(int, int), Long.toString(long, int)

      • deepEquals

        public static boolean deepEquals​(java.lang.Object obj1,
                                 java.lang.Object obj2)
        Compares two N-dimensional arrays and their contents recursively. It ignores the type of the arrays, so primitive and non-primitive arrays can be mixed.

        Examples

        
 deepEquals(1, 1) == true;
 deepEquals(0, 1) == false;
 deepEquals("text", "text") == true;
 deepEquals(new int[] {1, 2}, new int[] {1, 2}) == true;
 deepEquals(new int[] {1, 2}, new int[] {2, 1}) == false;
 deepEquals(new int[] {1, 2}, new Integer[] {1, 2}) == true;
 deepEquals(new Integer[][] {new Integer[] {1, 2}, new Integer[] {3, 4}},
         new int[][] {new int[] {1, 2}, new int[] {3, 4}}) == true;
 deepEquals(new int[][] {new int[] {1, 2}, new int[] {3, 4}},
         new int[][] {new int[] {9, 2}, new int[] {3, 4}}) == false;
        Parameters:
        obj1 - The first array to be compared.
        obj2 - The second array to be compared.
        Returns:
        true if both arrays and all their values are equal. false otherwise.
